      "title": "Studio Fredman: Fredrik Nordström's Direct Approach",
      "content": "Studio Fredman in Gothenburg was the creative hub of the 90s melodic death metal movement. Founded and operated by Fredrik Nordström, it served as the recording home for the core Gothenburg acts — At the Gates, In Flames, Dark Tranquillity, Hammerfall — and its production aesthetic became synonymous with the genre.\n\n**The Studio Fredman Drum Sound:**\nNordström's approach to drum recording emphasised directness over ambience. Unlike American metal productions of the same period that featured roomy, reverberant drum sounds, the Fredman approach was dry and tight:\n\n- Kick drums: AKG D112 or similar large-diaphragm dynamic, close-miked\n- Snare: Shure SM57 top — single mic, minimal processing\n- Toms: Sennheiser MD421 on each drum, tight and direct\n- Overheads: Minimal overhead contribution — close mics did the primary work\n- No room mics: The Fredman drum sound was constructed entirely from close-mic placement\n\n**Gating and Processing:**\nThe tight, punchy character of the Slaughter of the Soul drums is partly a product of aggressive gating. Each drum was gated to eliminate bleed between sources and reduce room ambience to near-zero. The result is the characteristic Gothenburg drum sound: clean, defined, and aggressive without wash or bloom.\n\n**The Production Context:**\nAt the Gates recorded Slaughter of the Soul quickly — the sessions were efficient by necessity, with the band's underground status limiting the available budget. Nordström worked fast, and the urgency of the recording environment is audible in the performance energy. The drums sound live and committed because they largely were — recorded without extensive editing or sample replacement.",
