      "title": "Nineteen Years Later: Adrian Erlandsson Returns to the Studio with At the Gates",
      "content": "At War with Reality, released on Century Media Records in late October 2014, is the album fans of At the Gates never expected to get: the band's first new studio material since Slaughter of the Soul in 1995. At the Gates had disbanded in 1996 at the height of their influence, reunited for live shows from 2007 onward, and finally committed to writing and recording new music together in 2013 — closing a 19-year gap that had, by that point, seen the Gothenburg melodic death metal sound they helped invent become one of the most widely imitated templates in extreme music.\n\nAdrian Erlandsson was back behind the kit for the sessions, recorded at the band's old home base, Studio Fredman in Gothenburg, between June 24 and July 18, 2014. Fredrik Nordström — the producer whose direct, dry drum sound had defined Slaughter of the Soul two decades earlier — returned as engineer, this time working alongside Henrik Udd, with Jens Bogren handling mixing and mastering at Fascination Street Studios. The pairing of Nordström's studio and Bogren's modern mix sensibility gave the album a sound that honored the band's 90s foundation while sitting comfortably next to 2014's heavier, more polished metal productions.\n\nErlandsson's drumming setup had changed dramatically in the years between the two albums. Where Slaughter of the Soul was tracked on unglamorous, undocumented studio house gear, At War with Reality captured him on the Tama Starclassic Bubinga rig he had developed across a career that took him through The Haunted, Cradle of Filth, and Paradise Lost — a mature, professional setup built for a drummer who by 2014 had spent nearly two decades touring and recording internationally at the highest level of extreme metal.\n\nThe album itself is a loose concept record inspired by magical realism and the short fiction of Jorge Luis Borges — track titles like \"The Circular Ruins\" and \"The Book of Sand\" draw directly from Borges' work. Musically, it picks up the Gothenburg thread where Slaughter of the Soul left it: tremolo-picked melodic riffing over relentless D-beat and blast-beat drumming, delivered with the same discipline that made the band's 90s work so influential. Commercially, it was a triumph, debuting at number three in Sweden and reaching number 53 on the Billboard 200 — remarkable chart positions for a band returning after nearly two decades away.\n\nThis article breaks down Adrian Erlandsson's drum setup for At War with Reality — the Tama Starclassic Bubinga kit, Sabian cymbal configuration, and the Studio Fredman/Fascination Street production chain that brought At the Gates' drummer back into the studio for the first time since 1995.",
