      "description": "For To Drink from the Night Itself, Erlandsson brought the same Tama Starclassic Bubinga kit he had used on At War with Reality four years earlier — a four-tom, double-22\" kick configuration in transparent black finish that had, by this point, become his settled, unchanging studio and touring rig. Unlike the jump from Slaughter of the Soul's undocumented studio gear to the professional Starclassic setup of the reunion era, the gap between At the Gates' two post-2007 studio albums shows no equipment change at all — a sign of a drummer who, by his late 40s and with decades of touring behind him, had found a setup that served every context from The Haunted's hardcore-inflected death metal to At the Gates' melodic aggression.\n\nWhat did change was the room: rather than returning to Studio Fredman, the band tracked at Parlour Recording Studios in Kettering, England, Russ Russell's own facility. Parlour's acoustic environment and Russell's recording approach — honed on records for Napalm Death, Dimmu Borgir, and Evile — gave the same Bubinga kit a different character than it had on At War with Reality, generally described as tighter and more aggressive in keeping with the album's darker thematic content.\n\nThe consistency of the underlying hardware across two very different recording environments and production teams is itself notable: the Starclassic Bubinga's dense low end and strong projection translate reliably regardless of studio, which is part of why Erlandsson has kept the same core kit configuration across nearly a decade of recordings by the time of this album.",
