      "title": "Russ Russell at Parlour Studios: A Different Room, A Darker Record",
      "content": "To Drink from the Night Itself marked the first time At the Gates recorded a reunion-era album away from Studio Fredman. Instead, the band tracked drums, bass, and guitars at Parlour Recording Studios in Kettering, England — Russ Russell's own facility — between November 12 and 26, 2017.\n\n**Russ Russell's Production Approach:**\nRussell, known for his work with Napalm Death, Dimmu Borgir, and Evile, served as producer alongside band members Jonas Björler and Tomas Lindberg Redant, and personally handled recording, mixing, and mastering — a more consolidated production credit than the multi-engineer, multi-studio chain (Nordström/Udd tracking, Bogren mixing) used on At War with Reality. This gave Russell tighter end-to-end control over the album's sound.\n\n**Split Recording Locations:**\nWhile the core rhythm section was tracked at Parlour, vocals were recorded separately at Welfare Studios in Gothenburg, and orchestral string parts — cello, violin, and double bass from guest musicians Rajmund Follmann, Tony Larsson, and Peter Nitsche — were recorded at Rovljud Studios in Örebro in December 2017, adding an atmospheric layer absent from the band's earlier, more stripped-down records.\n\n**A Darker Sonic Character:**\nThe combination of a new studio, a new lead guitarist in Jonas Stålhammar, and Russell's grinding production instincts gave To Drink from the Night Itself a tighter, more compressed, and more aggressive sound than At War with Reality's fuller Bogren mix — a sonic shift that mirrors the album's darker lyrical engagement with European nationalism and the refugee crisis of the mid-2010s.\n\n**Guest Contributions:**\nAndy LaRocque (King Diamond) contributed a guest guitar solo on \"In Nameless Sleep,\" one of several details that mark this as a more collaborative, expansive production than either of the band's previous two records.",
